node.text:
When it came time to create a name and a label for our collaboration with @18thstreetbrewery for @barrelandflow, illustrator, comic artist, and professor John Jennings was more than up to the job. John's a former Midwesterner who has worked on projects for Marvel Comics, adapted the legendary works of Octavia E. Butler, and served as the creative force for Shop Talk.⁠
⁠
"The themes around this beer were connection, African-American culture, safe spaces in Black communities and how all of that would resonate in an Afro-centric beer festival," Jennings said. "I thought about the Afro-futurist perspective, the Great Migration, the history of the South Side of Chicago. Just all kinds of ideas tumbling around in our heads." ⁠
⁠
Eventually, he came to the idea of Shop Talk – the common shared language of particular professions – and applying that to both breweries and the common cultural (and pop-cultural) barbershop space. Shop talk is an understanding, a common language, and the latest about the latest. ⁠
⁠
"I liked the idea of reclaiming the idea of this COVID-affected space. Barbershops were originally a place of literal healing, doctoring as well as haircuts. The red on the barber pole represents a wrapped wound, and a place of healing," Jennings said. "It's also a space immune to class or age. Whether you're 8 or 80, paying 2 dollars or 200, everybody needs a haircut. The space becomes familiar, and takes on a life of its own."⁠
⁠
The nexus of conversation, healing, and community drives not just the name of this beer, but what Barrel & Flow is all about. At its best, Jennings said, the barbershop represents an interstitial, liminal space in the same way that a crossroads, depot, or airport does depending on your cultural signifier of choice.  At first, there's a discomfort as a new entry to an established space. But soon after, you belong. Things are cool. It's conversation, it's familiarity, it's community. ⁠
⁠
We're happy to have @johnjenningsart, 18th Street, @daybracey, and everyone at Barrel & Flow as part of our community. We hope Shop Talk, the festival, and everything is between is just the start of new spaces, new conversations, and a new way forward.

- Two 3-day passes to @C2E2 (December 10 - December 12, 2021)⁠
- A two-night hotel stay at the @hyattchicago during C2E2 2021 weekend⁠
- Two tickets to the @360Chicago Observation Deck⁠
- A $100 Revolution Brewpub gift card⁠
- Rev swag, and more! ⁠
⁠
We're placing Golden Tickets into 30 different League of Heroes 12-packs. The winners will be randomly placed at retailers throughout Illinois, Indiana, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey, Ohio, Tennessee, and Wisconsin. Find one and you'll hang with us at C2E2 this December. ⁠
⁠
Good luck, adventurers!

node.text: Today we're "traveling" to begin a series against That Other Local Team We Will Not Name. We're looking forward to three games of domination, accompanied by fresh, cold beer. Cheers to Chicago's team.

node.text:
When creating Pursuit of Freedom: Yuzu Raspberry (available tomorrow at both locations), we wanted something bright, tart, and sweet to shine through the remainder of this fine summer. Enter the yuzu: a slow-growing citrus varietal originally from the eastern region of Asia with a tart flavor and a blooming citrus aroma. The flavor hits like a surging wave of grapefruit with a sweet undertow of mandarin orange.⁠
⁠
We paired this spectacular fruit with raspberries, which mirror the tart/sweet profile but also contribute floral and fresh-picked fruit notes. The resulting brew pours pink and drinks like a summer hammock dream. ⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Revolution Brewing on August 04, 2021. May be an image of drink and outdoors.

node.text:
We've been building our League of Heroes IPA Variety Packs on a theme for a bit more than a year now. And for this issue, released in the height of summer, we figured it was time to shoot for an ode to the blockbuster.⁠
⁠
The magic of any Summer blockbuster isn't in any one single element. It isn't the story, or the directing, or even the effects. (Even the acting didn't have to be top-notch. Van Damme had some great ones.) It's a combination of all those elements working together to form the purest, most perfect expression of entertainment. Straight dopamine with a theater-sized popcorn chaser. ⁠
⁠
We took that approach with Action-Hero, the debuting Hazy IPA in this latest League. Our fedora'd protagonist is built with Motueka as the box office draw, and it's an endlessly charismatic hop. ⁠
⁠
The New Zealand-born star sets out a tropical baseline, hinting at a lot of things but committing entirely to none. It's NOT mango, or orange, or lime zest, or pineapple, or coconut, or a million other things you can nail down. But it reminds you of the shared vibe within all of them, and it's as delicious and drinkable as it is inscrutable. Your best action stars share those same traits – difficult to nail down, impossible to pigeonhole, and unthinkable to turn away from. ⁠
⁠
From there, it's a who's-who of supporting stars and character roles: Best Supporting Citra; ruggedly handsome Amarillo; an encore for Cascade; and up-and-coming Sabro. Put all of them together and we think we've got a hit. ⁠
⁠
Get your ticket to the show now, via the shelves of finer retailers near you. Action-Hero and the rest of the League are ready for their closeup.

A quick update for our local friends and visitors: starting today, we'll again be requiring all customers over the age of two to wear masks at the Taproom and Brewpub. If you show up without a mask, not to worry, we'll have one ready for you. They can be removed when seated and eating/drinking. ⁠
⁠
Thanks in advance for your understanding and support, and we greatly appreciate your kindness to Rev Brew Crew members and each other.

node.text: The Royals are in town for three and the Sox are eight-and-a-half games up. Let's catch the rest of a year to remember with a cold Rev beer and a fine ballpark snack – Chicago style, of course.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Revolution Brewing on August 02, 2021. May be an image of road, sky and twilight.

node.text:
Let's hear it for the neighborhoods. The steel and glass looms ever-present in Chicago, and it's what everyone from elsewhere thinks about first. But you know, and we know, that the true soul of the place is in these two-flats, taverns, and five or six great places to get a dog or a gyro before you hit the next Alderman's patch.⁠
⁠
Logan Square is where we started, where we fought for years to get a brewery off the ground. And if this one doesn't do it for you, there are 76 others to choose from. (Give or take a few dozen more unofficial ones.)⁠
⁠
Here's to you neighborhood dwellers. We wish you porch beers, late nights, and a chance to leave your mark on this place. ⁠
⁠

node.text: There have been plenty of fireworks this year at Guaranteed Rate Field, and there are plenty more to come. Toast the next White Sox win with a fresh Anti-Hero, proudly brewed only in Chicago.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Revolution Brewing on July 29, 2021 tagging @darkmattercoffee. May be an image of drink and indoor.

node.text:
Supermassive Café Deth is percolating out to distribution in Illinois, Wisconsin, Indiana, and Ohio. If you hold the slightest affection for coffee in your heart (or even just enjoyed a cup of break room joe once) we think you'll be fairly thrilled at the result of six hundred and sixty six pounds of freshly roasted @darkmattercoffee beans.⁠
⁠
"Tastes like coffee"? Sure, if you prefer. But coffee, like beer, isn't just one flavor. It's a matrix of notes and aromas and temperature and time and all the other things that make tasting such a delight of a moving target. Mash up two of the world's greatest beverages and it's some advanced calculus that we didn't stick around the classroom long enough to explain in this venue.⁠
⁠
The midnight-black body coaxes forth the fudgy chocolate and warm toffee aromas of the bean. Meanwhile our old friend bourbon loudly clears its through, never letting you forget whose show this is. Each sip, coming clearer into view as your glass warms, arrives with thick, sweet notes of booze, oak, and the verdant complexities of coffee that we were just lecturing you about.⁠
⁠
This one's never going to be better than right now, and we already can't wait to brew it again.
